#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:2
msgid "Create Plugin"
msgstr ""

#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:5
msgid "Overview"
msgstr ""

#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:7
msgid "This plugin assists in the creation of a local plugin by preparing the plugin framework files and git repository."
msgstr ""

#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:11
msgid "What it Does"
msgstr ""

#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:13
msgid "It gathers some information from the user, and then writes the basic framework files to the specified directory and initializes the git repository."
msgstr ""

#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:15
msgid "Create Plugin UI"
msgstr ""

#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:20
msgid "Information input includes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:22
msgid "**Plugin Title**: A name for the plugin. This is used in the plugin's metadata and is how it will be displayed in Picard's plugin manager."
msgstr ""

#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:23
msgid "**Author Name**: The name of the plugin's author. This is used in the plugin's metadata."
msgstr ""

#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:24
msgid "**Author Email**: The email address of the plugin's author. This is used in the plugin's metadata as the mailto link for reporting issues, and for the initial commit to the git repository."
msgstr ""

#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:25
msgid "**Plugin Description**: A brief description of the plugin's functionality, and may contain markdown. This is used in the plugin's metadata, and is also added to the ``README.md`` file for the plugin. The plugin's short description is also added to the plugin's metadata, and is used in the plugin listing on the Picard website. The short description is generated by taking the first paragraph of the description, up to a maximum of 200 characters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:26
msgid "**License**: The license under which the plugin is distributed. This is used in the plugin's metadata. The license is selected from a list of common open source licenses. There is an option for \"Other\" or proprietary, which will allow you to specify a custom license; however, this will have to be entered into the plugin's ``MANIFEST.toml`` file manually."
msgstr ""

#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:27
msgid "**Target Directory**: The directory where the plugin files and git repository will be created."
msgstr ""

#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:28
msgid "**Plugin Categories**: The categories to which the plugin belongs. This is used in the plugin's metadata and is how the plugin will be categorized on the Picard website. Multiple categories can be selected for a plugin, and the categories are not mutually exclusive. If no categories are selected, then the plugin will be uncategorized on the Picard website."
msgstr ""

#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:30
msgid "There is also an option to create a plugin with multi-language support, which will create the necessary files and structure for supporting translations of the plugin's metadata and user interface. This option is recommended, as it allows for the plugin to be more easily translated in the future, and also provides a framework for handling translations of any user interface elements that the plugin may have. This option does not add any additional steps to the plugin creation process, and does not require any additional information from the user other than the base language for the plugin, but it does add some additional files and structure to the plugin framework that is created."
msgstr ""

#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:32
msgid "The final option is whether or not to create an initial commit to the git repository for the plugin. The default is to create an initial commit. The initial commit will be made with the generated plugin files, and the commit message will be \"Initial commit\". The author of the commit will be set to the name and email address provided in the plugin information. Regardless of the setting of this option, a git repository will be initialized in the target directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:34
msgid "Once you have entered all of the required information and selected the desired options, you can click the :guilabel:`Create` button to create the plugin framework files and git repository in the specified target directory. The system first checks that the target directory exists or can be created, and that it has not already been initialized as a git repository. You will then be prompted to confirm whether or not you want to proceed with creating the plugin files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:38
msgid "It is recommended to review the information you have entered and confirm that it is correct before proceeding, as the plugin files will be generated and the git repository will be initialized based on the information you have provided. It is especially important to double-check the target directory. If you need to make any changes to the information you have entered, you can click :guilabel:`No` to return to the plugin creation form and make any necessary changes before confirming again. Items such as plugin title, author information, and description can be edited in the generated files later if necessary."
msgstr ""

#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:40
msgid "When you have confirmed, the plugin will generate the necessary files for the plugin framework, including an ``__init__.py`` file, a ``MANIFEST.toml`` file with the plugin metadata, and a ``README.md`` file with the plugin description. If multi-language support was selected, then additional files and structure will be created for handling translations. A git repository with a ``.gitignore`` file will also be initialized in the target directory. If the option to create an initial commit was selected, then an initial commit will be made with the generated plugin files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:42
msgid "Once the plugin has been created, you can then open the target directory in your file browser or terminal to view the generated files and git repository. You can then customize the generated plugin files as needed to implement the desired functionality for your plugin. You can also use the initialized git repository to manage the version control for your plugin development."
msgstr ""

#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:46
msgid "Option Settings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:48
msgid "Once you have created a plugin, the following settings are remembered for the next time it is used:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:50
msgid "Author Name"
msgstr ""

#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:51
msgid "Author Email"
msgstr ""

#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:52
msgid "License"
msgstr ""

#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:53
msgid "Whether or not to create an initial commit to the git repository"
msgstr ""

#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:54
msgid "Whether or not to create a plugin with multi-language support, and the base language for the plugin if multi-language support is enabled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../create_plugin/user_guide.rst:56
msgid "In addition, the parent directory of the last target directory used for creating a plugin is also remembered. This is used as the starting point for the directory browser when selecting a target directory for creating a future plugin, and can make it more convenient to create and select a target directory if you are creating multiple plugins in the same parent directory."
msgstr ""

